column3: Cattle Death Loss: Released May 5, 2006, by the National Agricultural Statistics Service (NASS), Agricultural Statistics Board, U.S. Department of Agriculture.
Losses of Cattle and Calves:  Predator and Non-Predator
Number of Head and Total Value, United States, 2005 1/

1/  Totals may not add due to rounding.  Cattle includes all cows, bulls, steers, and heifers weighing over 500 pounds.  This includes beef and milk breeds as well as cattle on feed.  Calves include beef and milk breed steers, heifers, and bulls weighing less than 500 pounds.

3/  Reports of death loss to cattle/calves by vultures is primarily due to black vultures and will occur only in states where this species ranges.  See range map of black vultures at:  http:/www.birds.cornell.edu/AllAboutBirds/Bird Guide/Black_Vulture_dtl.html map.
4/  The category of unknown predators was not included in the 'Cattle Predator Loss' report released May 2001.

Cattle Death Loss: Released May 5, 2006, by the National Agricultural Statistics Service (NASS), Agricultural Statistics Board, U.S. Department of Agriculture.
Losses of Cattle and Calves from Predators and Non-Predator Causes:
Total Value per Head and Total Value, by State and United States, 2005 1/
1/  Missing data are less than 100 head for the State or not published to avoid disclosure of individual operations.  This data is included in the Unpublished States and in the United States.
2/  Cattle value per head is based on a two-year straight average of the value of beef cows reported in the January 1 Cattle survey from 2005 and 2006.
3/  Calf value per head is based on the market year average calf price.  An average weight of 300 pounds was used in all States.
4/  U.S. value per head rounded to the nearest dollar.  U.S. value per head derived.  Totals may not add due to rounding.
